# Pulse

Pulse is a lightweight, agent-driven system monitoring project built as a hobby project to explore telemetry collection, persistent metrics storage, event detection, and dashboard visualization.

The project consists of:

- A Go backend API
- Lightweight monitoring agents
- SQLite persistent storage
- A React dashboard built with Vite
- Recharts-based metric visualization
- A derived event detection system

## Current Status

Pulse is under active development.

The current version supports multi-host metric collection, persistent historical storage, time-range filtering, live dashboard visualization, host health status, and derived system events.

## Features

### Metric Collection

Pulse agents report:

- CPU usage
- RAM usage
- Load average
- System uptime
- Hostname
- Timestamp

Metrics are pushed from agents to the Pulse server and stored persistently in SQLite.

### Multi-Host Monitoring

The dashboard supports multiple reporting hosts.

Users can select a host and inspect its:

- Historical metrics
- Statistics
- Recent events
- Current reporting status

### Dashboard

The React dashboard currently includes:

- Host selector
- CPU graph
- RAM graph
- Load average graph
- Time-range selection
  - 1 hour
  - 6 hours
  - 24 hours
  - 7 days
- Dynamic statistics cards
- Current host status
- Last-seen information
- Current uptime
- Latest CPU and RAM values
- Recent event timeline

### Event Detection

Pulse derives events from historical telemetry.

Currently supported events:

- System reboot detected
- High CPU usage detected
- CPU usage returned to normal
- High RAM usage detected
- RAM usage returned to normal

Threshold events use state transitions to avoid generating repeated alerts for every metric sample.

Hysteresis is used to reduce event flapping around alert thresholds.

### Host Status

Pulse derives reporting health from the timestamp of the latest received metric.

Current states include:

- Reporting
- Delayed
- Not reporting
- Unknown

This represents telemetry/reporting health and does not necessarily mean the physical machine is offline.

## Architecture

```text
Monitoring Agent
      |
      | HTTP / JSON
      v
Go Backend API
      |
      v
SQLite Database
      |
      +------------------+
      |                  |
      v                  v
Metrics API         Event Derivation
      |                  |
      +--------+---------+
               |
               v
        React Dashboard

### Tech Stack
### Backend
- Go
- net/http
- SQLite
- JSON API

### Frontend
- React
- Vite
- Recharts
- JavaScript
- CSS

### API endpoints
/metrics
/metrics/latest
/stats
/events

### Examples
curl "http://localhost:8080/metrics?host=RaikariLinux&hours=24"
curl "http://localhost:8080/events?host=RaikariLinux&hours=168"
curl "http://localhost:8080/metrics/latest?host=RaikariLinux"

## Event Flow
CPU normal
    |
    v
CPU crosses high threshold
    |
    v
High CPU event
    |
    v
CPU remains high
(no repeated events)
    |
    v
CPU crosses recovery threshold
    |
    v
CPU normal event

